  <discussion>Syntrichia obtusissima, with a distinctive Southwest and Mexican-Andean disjunction, has been much confused with S. ruralis, leading to many misidentified specimens in herbaria, but the large, pellucid leaf cells (about 15–23 µm) contrast with those of S. ruralis (about 8–12 µm), and the back of the costa lacks serrations from projecting cell ends.  Furthermore, it has a clear central strand in the stem, and hydroids in the costa, neither of which is found in S. ruralis.</discussion>
